data.content:
**Yes, C# fully supports `stackalloc`'d `Span<nint>` and `Span<nuint>`.** Both work without requiring `unsafe` context. On this 64-bit system, `nint` is 8 bytes and everything behaves as expected:

```csharp
Span<nint> values = stackalloc nint[5];
Span<nuint> unsigned = stackalloc nuint[3];
```

The one minor gotcha: `sizeof(nint)` requires an `unsafe` context (since the size isn't fixed at compile time), but you can use `nint.Size` instead.
